\begin_layout Subsection
The Gelfond-Parry measure
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This measure is given by eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

 and is given by Gelfond
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Gelfond59"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and by Parry
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Parry60"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Unfortunately, I find the Russian original of Gelfond's article unreadable,
 and Parry's work, stemming from his PhD thesis, is not available online.
 Therefore, it is of some interest to provide a proof suitable for the current
 text.
 A generalization of this proof is used to construct general eigenfunctions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The easiest route seems to be direct verification that eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

 is correct, as opposed to a derivation of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:invariant measure"

\end_inset

 from first principles.
 This is done below, explicitly showing all steps in laborious detail.
 It's not at all difficult; just a bit hard on the eyes.
 As before, let 
\begin_inset Formula $t\left(x\right)\equiv t_{\beta}\left(x\right)=\beta x\mod1$
\end_inset

 be the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transformation of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:beta transform"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 the iterated transformation.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta(x)$
\end_inset

 be the Heaviside step function as always, and to keep notation brief, let
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}\equiv t^{n}\left(1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The Gelfond-Parry measure is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu\left(y\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(t_{n}-y\right)}{\beta^{n}}
\]

\end_inset

where it is more convenient to write 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{n}\left(y\right)=\Theta\left(t_{n}-y\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The transfer operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

 for the beta-transformation is slightly more convenient to work with than
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 for this particular case.
 It is given by 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{M}f\right]\left(y\right)=\frac{1}{\beta}\left[f\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+f\left(\frac{y+1}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right)\right]
\]

\end_inset

and we wish to verify that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\nu=\nu$
\end_inset

.
 Plugging in directly,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P=\nu\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+\nu\left(\frac{y+1}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right) & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{y+1}{\beta}\right)\Theta\left(\beta-1-y\right)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1-y\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\Theta\left(ax\right)=\Theta\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for all constants 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

, and since 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}\le1$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
 These terms simplify, depending on whether 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 is small or large.
 Explicitly, one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1-y\right)=0 & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1<0\\
\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-y\right)=1 & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1>0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(1-\beta t_{n}\right)\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\left(1+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1-y\right)\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

These can be collapsed by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\beta t_{n}=t_{n+1} & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1<0\\
\beta t_{n}-1=t_{n+1} & \mbox{ if }\beta t_{n}-1>0
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
P & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(1-\beta t_{n}\right)\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\left(1+\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)\right)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)\left[\Theta\left(1-\beta t_{n}\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\right]+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\right)\\
 & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{1}{\beta^{n}}\left(\Theta\left(t_{n+1}-y\right)+\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)\right)\\
 & =\beta\nu\left(y\right)-\beta+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)}{\beta^{n}}\\
 & =\beta\nu\left(y\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The last sum on the right is just the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion for 1.
 That is, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
x=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t^{n}\left(x\right)-1\right)}{\beta^{n+1}}
\]

\end_inset

This is just eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shift series"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 written in a different way (making use of the equivalence 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xform-shift equivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula $P=\beta\nu\left(y\right)$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}\nu=\nu$
\end_inset

 as claimed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analytic Gelfond-Parry function
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Rotated-Renyi-Parry-function"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The steps performed above can be repeated verbatim for a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rotated
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

coherent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 function
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\nu_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}\frac{\Theta\left(t_{n}-y\right)}{\beta^{n}}\label{eq:generalized-eigenfunction}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

for some complex-valued 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

.
 No changes are required, and the result can be read off directly:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[\mathcal{M}\nu_{\beta;z}\right]\left(y\right) & =\frac{\nu_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)}{z}-\frac{1}{z}+\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}z^{n}\frac{\Theta\left(\beta t_{n}-1\right)}{\beta^{n+1}}\\
 & =\frac{\nu_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)}{z}+C\left(\beta;z\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

 being a constant independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 If there are values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 at which 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)=0$
\end_inset

, then this becomes the eigenequation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{M}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The eigenfunction for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}$
\end_inset

 is the same, up to rescaling of 
\begin_inset Formula $y\mapsto\beta x/2$
\end_inset

.
 Recycling notation slightly, write
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
v_{\beta;z}\left(x\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{d_{n}\left(x\right)}{\beta^{n}}z^{n}\label{eq:coherent-first-order}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 are exactly the same digits as defined by Parry, just rescaled for the
 beta-shift.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{n}\left(x\right)=\varepsilon_{n}\left(\frac{2x}{\beta}\right)=\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}t_{n}-x\right)=\Theta\left(T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)-x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{if }x<T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 the beta-shift map of eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

 and eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:xform-shift equivalence"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is used.
 The iterated end-point becomes the iterated midpoint:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
t^{n}\left(1\right)=\frac{2}{\beta}T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Holding both 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 fixed, the summation is clearly convergent (and holomorphic in 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

) for complex numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 within the disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|<\beta$
\end_inset

.
 The eigenequation has the same form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}v_{\beta;z}\right]\left(x\right)=\frac{1}{z}v_{\beta;z}\left(x\right)+C\left(\beta;z\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

 is a constant independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 Numeric verification reveals we were a bit glib: 
\begin_inset Formula $C\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

 is a constant for 
\begin_inset Formula $x<\beta/2$
\end_inset

 and is zero otherwise!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The interesting limit is where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|\to\beta$
\end_inset

 and so its convenient to re-express 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=z/\beta$
\end_inset

.
 With some rearrangements, one obtains
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)\equiv\zeta\beta C\left(\beta;\zeta\beta\right)=-1+\zeta\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}d_{n}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\label{eq:holomorphic-disk}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

The primary task is to characterize the zeros of 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This is a straight-forward sum to examine numerically; results will be
 presented in the section after the next.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Analytic ergodics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constant term can be independently derived through a different set of
 manipulations.
 Explicitly plugging in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:coherent-first-order"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 into the transfer operator yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
C\left(\beta;z\right)= & \left[\mathcal{L}_{\beta}v_{\beta;z}\right]\left(y\right)-\frac{v_{\beta;z}\left(y\right)}{z}\\
= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{z^{n}}{\beta^{n}}\left[\frac{1}{\beta}\left[d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)-\frac{1}{z}d_{n}\left(y\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=z/\beta$
\end_inset

 gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)= & \zeta\beta C\left(\beta;\zeta\beta\right)\\
= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\left[\zeta\left[d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)-d_{n}\left(y\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This is holomorphic on the unit disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|<1$
\end_inset

, as each individual 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 is either zero or one; there won't be any poles inside the unit disk.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}\left(y\right)=0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y>\beta/2$
\end_inset

, and so one may pull out the step function to write 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\left[\zeta d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}\right)+\zeta d_{n}\left(\frac{y}{\beta}+\frac{1}{2}\right)-d_{n}\left(y\right)\right]\Theta\left(\frac{\beta}{2}-y\right)
\]

\end_inset

confirming the earlier numerical observation that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 vanishes for all 
\begin_inset Formula $y>\beta/2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The bottom equation holds without assuming that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 However, we've already proven that it is; and so a simplified expression
 can be given simply by picking a specific 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Setting 
\begin_inset Formula $y=0$
\end_inset

, noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}\left(0\right)=1$
\end_inset

 and canceling terms, one obtains eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 again.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Staring at the right-hand side of the sum above, it is hardly obvious that
 it should be independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 In a certain sense, this is not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

one equation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, this holds for a continuum of 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, for all 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le y\le1$
\end_inset

.
 It is an analytic equation tying together the entire subshift.
 For each distinct 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, it singles out three completely different bit-sequences out of the subshift,
 and ties them together.
 It is a form of mixing.
 Alternately, a form of interaction: the bit-sequences are not independent
 of one-another; they interact.
 This section attempts to make these notions more precise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The tying-together of seemingly unrelated sequences seems somehow terribly
 important.
 It is tempting to give this some silly name, such as the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fundamental theorem of analytic ergodics
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's be exceptionally clear about the meaning: equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 defined a map, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift.
 Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 defined a bit-sequence, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le x\le1$
\end_inset

, where equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:shift series"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is the definition of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-expansion.
 The set of all such bit-sequences defines the shift.
 To emphasize the point, its best to compare side-by-side.
 Copying equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:down-bits"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, we had 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
k_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
0 & \mbox{ if }0\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)<\frac{1}{2}\\
1 & \mbox{ if }\frac{1}{2}\le T_{\beta}^{n}(x)\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

 while
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{n}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
1 & \mbox{if }x<T^{n}\left(\frac{\beta}{2}\right)=T^{n+1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)\\
0 & \mbox{otherwise}
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

The iterations are running in opposite directions; this is as appropriate,
 since the the transfer operator was a push-forward.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is useful here to return to the language of cylinder sets, as opposed
 to point dynamics.
 Recall that the Borel algebra 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 was defined as the sigma algebra, the collection of all cylinder sets in
 the product topology of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ 0,1\right\} ^{\omega}$
\end_inset

.
 A subshift is a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{S}\subset\mathcal{B}$
\end_inset

 together with a map 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 that lops off the leading symbol of a given cylinder set but otherwise
 preserves the subshift: 
\begin_inset Formula $T\mathcal{S}=\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

.
 The inverted map 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}$
\end_inset

 is a pushforward, in that it defines the transfer operator, a linear operator
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:\mathcal{F\to\mathcal{F}}$
\end_inset

 on the space 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 of all functions 
\begin_inset Formula $f:\mathcal{S}\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

; explicitly, it is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{T}:f\mapsto f\circ T^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Insofar as the 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 arose in the exploration of the transfer operator, it is not surprising
 that the shift is acting 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

backwards
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The problem with point dynamics is that one cannot meaningfully write 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 for a real number, a point 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, at least, not without sever contortions that lead back to the Borel algebra.
 Not for lack of trying; the 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is called the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

Julia set
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 (to order 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

) of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: it is the preimage, the set of all points that, when iterated, converge
 onto 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Can the analytic relation be restated in terms of cylinder sets? Yes, and
 it follows in a fairly natural way.
 The first step is to extend 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}$
\end_inset

 to a map 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{n}:\mathcal{S}\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu:\mathcal{B}\to\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 be the Bernoulli measure.
 Using the Bernoulli mapping 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:homomorphism"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,T^{n}\left(\beta/2\right)\right]$
\end_inset

 maps to some cylinder; call it 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Then, given some cylinder 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, define
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
d_{n}\left(A\right)=\mu\left(A\cap\Delta_{n}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The rotated (pre-)measure is extended likewise: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\nu\left(A\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}d_{n}\left(A\right)
\]

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta=z/\beta$
\end_inset

 as before, recovering the Parry measure by setting 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

.
 The Parry measure should be invariant under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{-1}:\mathcal{S}\to\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

, and otherwise yield eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's check.
 The proof will mirror the one of the previous section.
 Here, it is convenient to use the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-transform 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 instead of the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 This is primarily a conceptual convenience; the subshift is more easily
 visualized in terms of the mod 1 map.
 Otherwise, the same notation is used, but rescaled, so that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{n}$
\end_inset

 is the cylinder corresponding to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,t^{n}\left(1\right)\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that for every 
\begin_inset Formula $A\in\mathcal{S}$
\end_inset

 and every 
\begin_inset Formula $y\in A$
\end_inset

, one will find that 
\begin_inset Formula $y/\beta\in t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 and, whenever 
\begin_inset Formula $y\le\beta-1$
\end_inset

 that also 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(y+1\right)/\beta\in t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

 naturally splits into two parts: the cylinder that maps to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1/\beta\right]$
\end_inset

, call it 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and the complement 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{D}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The pushfoward action is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu\left(t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\\
= & \sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\left[\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)+\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\right]
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Two distinct cases emerge.
 When 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}\left(1\right)<1/\beta$
\end_inset

 then one has that 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}=\varnothing$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the second term can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right) & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap\overline{D}\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\\
 & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\frac{1}{\beta}\mu\left(\Delta_{n+1}\cap A\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the second line follows from the first by linearity, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\overline{D}$
\end_inset

 selected out one of the two branches of 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{-1}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Meanwhile, when 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{n}\left(1\right)>1/\beta$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $D\subset\Delta_{n}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $D\cap\Delta_{n}=D$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, the first term splits into two: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right) & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\mu\left(D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)\\
 & =\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\frac{1}{\beta}\mu\left(A\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

while
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\Theta\left(\frac{1}{\beta}-t_{n}\right)\mu\left(\Delta_{n}\cap D\cap t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right)=\Theta\left(\frac{1}{\beta}-t_{n}\right)\frac{1}{\beta}\mu\left(\Delta_{n+1}\cap A\right)
\]

\end_inset

Reassembling these pieces and making use of 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta_{0}\cap A=A$
\end_inset

 one gets
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\nu\left(t^{-1}\left(A\right)\right) & =\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\zeta^{n}}{\beta}\left[\mu\left(A\right)\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)+\mu\left(\Delta_{n+1}\cap A\right)\right]\\
 & =\frac{1}{z}\nu\left(A\right)-\frac{\mu\left(A\right)}{z}+\mu\left(A\right)\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\frac{\zeta^{n}}{\beta}\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\\
 & =\frac{1}{z}\nu\left(A\right)+\frac{\mu\left(A\right)}{z}E\left(\beta;z\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with the constant term as before, in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:holomorphic-disk"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

:
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E\left(\beta;z\right) & =-1+\zeta\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}\Theta\left(t_{n}-\frac{1}{\beta}\right)\\
 & =-1+\zeta\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}\zeta^{n}d_{n}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

As before, one has for 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

 that 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;1\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu\circ t^{-1}=\nu$
\end_inset

 is indeed the measure invariant under 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{-1}$
\end_inset

.
 Other eigenvalues can be found for those values of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;z\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The task at hand is then to characterize 
\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
