\begin_inset Formula $E\left(\beta;z\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The function is easily explored numerically.
 It is clearly convergent in the unit disk 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|<1$
\end_inset

 and has no poles in the disk.
 For almost all 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, there seem to be a countable number of zeros within the disk, accumulating
 uniformly on the boundary as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\zeta\right|\to1$
\end_inset

.
 The notion of 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

uniformly
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

