\begin_layout Standard
The iteration of the midpoint 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{0}=\beta/2$
\end_inset

, that is, the iterated series 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{n}=T_{\beta}^{n}\left(\beta/2\right)$
\end_inset

 is ergodic in the unit interval, for almost all values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 However, for certain values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, the midpoint iterates will hit the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-shift map has a discontinuity.
 Here, iteration stops: at the next step, this point is defined to iterate
 to zero, in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

.
 Zero is a fixed point, and so there is nowhere further to go.
 This section explores these special values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside from the definition in eqn 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

, one can consider the modified map, where the less-than sign has been altered
 to a less-than-or-equals:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}^{\le}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\beta x & \mbox{ for }0\le x\le\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}<x\le1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

In this map, the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x=1/2$
\end_inset

 iterates to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2$
\end_inset

, which is just the initial midpoint itself.
 In this case, the halted orbits become periodic orbits.
 There is a third possibility, to simply remove the points 0, 1 and 1/2
 from the domain:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T_{\beta}^{<}\left(x\right)=\begin{cases}
\beta x & \mbox{ for }0<x<\frac{1}{2}\\
\beta\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}<x<1
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

In this case, if the midpoint iterates to 1/2, it can be taken to simply
 have wandered out of the domain of validity.
 The word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wander
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is used here in the technical sense: The map 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 is dissipative in two different senses: first, in the obvious sense, the
 points 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/2<x$
\end_inset

 wander away after exactly one iteration; secondly, the mid-point iterates
 wander down to zero, never to return, unless they are made explicitly periodic
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{\beta}^{\le}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All three variants can be considered together, so that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

true
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 beta shift is taken as the quotient space or identification space
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "WP-Quotient-Space"
literal "true"

\end_inset

 of the three variants, in the strict topological sense of a quotient space.
 Thus, interestingly, for the beta shift, the periodic orbits and the fixed
 point both belong to the same equivalence class.
 This has some interesting implications when one compares the beta shift
 to other iterated maps, such as the logistic map, which have non-trivial
 stable regions.
 Topologically, it would seem that one can perform a kind of surgery, attaching
 stable regions exactly into those spots where, in the beta shift, one has
 an equivalence class.
 This solves (at least for me) the long-standing problem of exactly how
 to properly describe the topological conjugacy between different kinds
 of iterated maps.
\end_layout

