\begin_layout Subsection
Complex Roots
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What are the complex roots? Numerical work clearly indicates that they seem
 to be approximately cyclotomic in some sense or another.
 They seem to be more-or-less uniformly distributed in an approximate circle,
 always.
 The modulus of most of the complex roots appear to be less than one.
 This is violated for the complex roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2^{k}}\left(\beta\right)=\beta^{k+2}-\beta^{k+1}-1$
\end_inset

, where some of the roots in the right-hand quadrant have a modulus larger
 than one.
 By contrast, the complex roots of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{2^{k}-1}\left(\beta\right)=\beta^{k+1}-\sum_{j=0}^{k}\beta^{j}$
\end_inset

 seem to always have a modulus less than one.
 These two seem to be the extreme cases: in general, the polynomials appear
 to be 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

approximately cyclotomic
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Its not clear how to make this statement more precise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These numerical results can be argued heuristically: just divide the polynomial
 by it's leading order.
 That is, a general polynomial of this form is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}-\sum_{j=0}^{k}b_{j}z^{k-j}
\]

\end_inset

with the convention that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=b_{k}=1$
\end_inset

, and the bit-sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $n=b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{p}$
\end_inset

 corresponding to a terminating orbit.
 Dividing by 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{k+1}$
\end_inset

gives a series 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1-\frac{1}{z}-\frac{b_{1}}{z^{2}}-\frac{b_{2}}{z^{3}}-\cdots
\]

\end_inset

Clearly, this can have a zero only when 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|z\right|<2$
\end_inset

 as otherwise, the terms get too small too quickly.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Golden 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-Fibonacci Sequences
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is well known that the golden ratio occurs as limit of the ratio of adjacent
 Fibonacci numbers:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\varphi=\lim_{m\to\infty}\frac{F_{m}}{F_{m-1}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}=F_{m-1}+F_{m-2}$
\end_inset

.
 There is a generalization of this, which also has received attention: the
 tribonacci, quadronacci, 
\emph on
etc
\emph default
.
 sequences, whose limits are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha_{n}=\lim_{m\to\infty}\frac{F_{m}^{(n)}}{F_{m-1}^{(n)}}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{m}^{(n)}=F_{m-1}^{(n)}+F_{m-2}^{(n)}+\cdots+F_{m-n}^{(n)}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Is it possible that the real roots of the polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}(\beta)$
\end_inset

 are also the roots of such sequences? But of course they are! Given a finite
 string of binary digits 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =b_{0},b_{1},\cdots,b_{k}$
\end_inset

, write the beta-Fibonacci sequence as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{m}^{\{b\}}=b_{0}F_{m-1}^{\{b\}}+b_{1}F_{m-2}^{\{b\}}+\cdots b_{k}F_{m-k}^{\{b\}}
\]

\end_inset

The name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

beta-Fibonacci
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is needed because the term 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

generalized Fibonacci sequence
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is already in wide circulation for the special case of all bits being one.
 The ratio of successive terms is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{\{b\}}=\lim_{m\to\infty}\frac{F_{m}^{\{b\}}}{F_{m-1}^{\{b\}}}
\]

\end_inset

and is given as the (positive) real root of the polynomial
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}\left(\beta\right)=\beta^{k+1}-b_{0}\beta^{k}-b_{1}\beta^{k-1}-\cdots-b_{k}=0
\]

\end_inset

These polynomials and their roots were already enumerated and tabulated
 in the previous section.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beta-Fibonacci sequences do not appear by accident: these sequences
 have an ordinary generating function (OGF) given by the polynomial! That
 is,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{m=0}^{\infty}z^{m}F_{m}^{\{b\}}=\frac{z^{k}}{1-b_{0}z-b_{1}z^{2}-\cdots-b_{k}z^{k+1}}=\frac{1}{zp_{n}\left(\frac{1}{z}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

The factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $z^{k}$
\end_inset

 in the numerator serves only to initiate the sequence so that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}^{\{b\}}=\cdots=F_{k-1}^{\{b\}}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{k}^{\{b\}}=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These sequences are generic: they indicate how many different ways one can
 partition the integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 into elements of the set 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{0},2b_{1},3b_{2},\cdots,\left(k+1\right)b_{k}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 So, for example, the entry for 
\begin_inset Formula $n=12$
\end_inset

 in the table below corresponds to OEIS A079971, which describes the number
 of ways an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 can be partitioned into 1, 2 and 5 (or that 
\begin_inset Formula $5m$
\end_inset

 can be partitioned into nickels, dimes and quarters).
 This corresponds to the bit sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b\right\} =11001$
\end_inset

; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ b_{0},2b_{1},3b_{2},\cdots,\left(k+1\right)b_{k}\right\} =\left\{ 1\cdot1,2\cdot1,3\cdot0,4\cdot0,5\cdot1\right\} =\left\{ 1,2,5\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 From such partitions, it appears that one can build partitions of the positive
 integers that are disjoint, and whose union is the positive integers.
 This suggests a question: can these partitions be expressed as Beatty sequences
?
\end_layout

