	filename period-n16.eps
	width 60col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The order of 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }$
\end_inset

 is six, and this has six almost-plateaus; they are not quite flat, although
 they are close to it, presumably because 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 is close to one.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The general case
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Generalizing from the above, one finds the following:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a period-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 orbit, the infinite series is 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\cdots\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)=q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)/\left(1-\zeta^{k}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The first label 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

 has a complex zero within the disk is 
\begin_inset Formula $n=16$
\end_inset

.
 As a general rule, it seems that complex zeros inside the disk only appear
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<\varphi$
\end_inset

 (I believe; have not carefully checked.
 This seems reasonable, as later chapters show that the region of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta<\varphi$
\end_inset

 behaves very differently from larger values.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The invariant measure has 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 plateaus.
 The plateau boundaries are given by 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{m}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\left\{ 0,\cdots,k-1\right\} $
\end_inset

 (so that 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{0}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{1}\left(\frac{1}{2}\right)=\frac{\beta}{2}$
\end_inset

, and so on).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The left-most plateau (of the invariant measure) is at 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta/\left(\beta-1\right)=\sum_{n=0}^{\infty}1/\beta^{n}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The other plateaus appear to be at simple rational functions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, but a precise expression is elusive.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solve the last issue, perhaps one can find tools in Galois theory.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}\left[\zeta\right]$
\end_inset

 be the ring of polynomials in 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta$
\end_inset

 and consider the quotient ring 
\begin_inset Formula $L=\mathbb{R}\left[\zeta\right]/q^{\left\{ b\right\} }\left(\zeta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 is a field extension of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and so one expects a Galois group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mbox{Gal}\left(L/\mathbb{R}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The plateaus of the invariant measure are presumably associated with the
 group elements.
 This seems like a promising direction to go in: perhaps this is just enough
 to explain the length of an orbit, the sequence of points in the orbit,
 the reason that some polynomials are forbidden (they don't generate prime
 ideals), the appearance of Moreau's necklace-counting function,
\emph on
 etc
\emph default
.
 This remains an unfinished exercise.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Factorization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The polynomials factorize.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{n}$
\end_inset

 denote the real positive root of 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 – that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}\left(r_{n}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Then one has the factorizations (dropping the subscript on 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 for readability)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}\left(x\right)=x^{2}-x-1=\left(x-r\right)\left(x+r-1\right)=\left(x-r\right)\left(x+p_{0}\left(r\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}\left(x\right)=x-1$
\end_inset

.
 Likewise, there are two order-3 polynomials.
 They factor as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{2}\left(x\right)=x^{3}-x-1=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{2}+xp_{0}\left(r\right)+rp_{0}\left(r\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

while
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{3}\left(x\right)=x^{3}-x^{2}-x-1=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{2}+xp_{0}\left(r\right)+p_{1}\left(r\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

Continuing in this way, there are three order-4 polynomials.
 They factor as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{7}\left(x\right)=x^{4}-x^{3}-x^{2}-x-1=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{3}+x^{2}p_{0}\left(r\right)+xp_{1}\left(r\right)+p_{3}\left(r\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{6}\left(x\right)=x^{4}-x^{3}-x^{2}-1=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{3}+x^{2}p_{0}\left(r\right)+xp_{1}\left(r\right)+rp_{1}\left(r\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset

and (noting that there is no 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{5}$
\end_inset

 that occurs in the series)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{4}\left(x\right)=x^{4}-x^{3}-1=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{3}+x^{2}p_{0}\left(r\right)+xrp_{0}\left(r\right)+r^{2}p_{0}\left(r\right)\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There's clearly a progression, but perhaps a bit difficult to grasp.
 It can be more clearly seen by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{n}=q_{2n+1}$
\end_inset

 and then writing out 
\begin_inset Formula $2n+1$
\end_inset

 in binary.
 So, once again, from the top:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{1}\left(x\right)=q_{11}\left(x\right)=\left(x-r\right)\left(x+q_{1}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}=q_{1}\left(r\right)$
\end_inset

 which adopts the shorthand that the 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 polynomials on the right-hand side always have 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 as an argument, which can be dropped for clarity.
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}\left(r\right)=r$
\end_inset

 was already previously observed, in an earlier section.
 That is, using the dropped-
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 convention, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{0}=r$
\end_inset

.
 Next
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{2}\left(x\right)=q_{101}\left(x\right)=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{2}+xq_{1}+q_{01}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{01}\left(x\right)\equiv rq_{1}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Next,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{3}\left(x\right)=q_{111}\left(x\right)=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{2}+xq_{1}+q_{11}\right)
\]

\end_inset

is the second factorization of order 3.
 For order 4, one has
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{4}\left(x\right)=q_{1001}\left(x\right)=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{3}+x^{2}q_{1}+xq_{01}+q_{001}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where, this time, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{001}\left(x\right)=xq_{01}\left(x\right)=x^{2}q_{1}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Continuing,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{6}\left(x\right)=q_{1101}\left(x\right)=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{3}+x^{2}q_{1}+xq_{11}+q_{011}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where, by definition, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{011}\left(x\right)\equiv xq_{11}\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Finally,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{7}\left(x\right)=q_{1111}\left(x\right)=\left(x-r\right)\left(x^{3}+x^{2}q_{1}+xq_{11}+q_{111}\right)
\]

\end_inset

It is worth doing one more, just to clinch that the reversal of the bit
 sequence is indeed correct.
 For this purpose, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{12}=q_{11001}$
\end_inset

 should serve well.
 One has
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p_{12}\left(x\right)=q_{11001}\left(x\right)= & \left(x-r\right)\left(x^{4}+x^{3}p_{0}\left(r\right)+x^{2}p_{1}\left(r\right)+xrp_{1}\left(r\right)+r^{2}p_{1}\left(r\right)\right)\\
= & \left(x-r\right)\left(x^{4}+x^{3}q_{1}+x^{2}q_{11}+xq_{011}+q_{0011}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general pattern should now be clear.
 Given one of the admissible bit sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{k-1}b_{k}$
\end_inset

 and recalling that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}=1$
\end_inset

 always, (and that 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 always) one has 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p_{n}\left(z\right)=q_{b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{k-1}b_{k}}\left(z\right)=z^{k+1}-b_{0}z^{k}-b_{1}z^{k-1}-\cdots-b_{k-1}z-1
\]

\end_inset

which has the factorization, with bits reversed:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{k-1}b_{k}}\left(z\right)=\left(z-r\right)\left(z^{k}+z^{k-1}q_{b_{0}}+z^{k-2}q_{b_{1}b_{0}}+z^{k-3}q_{b_{2}b_{1}b_{0}}+\cdots+q_{b_{k-1}b_{k-2}\cdots b_{1}b_{0}}\right)
\]

\end_inset

where, as already noted, each 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

 is a polynomial in the root 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Although, notationally, the root 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 was taken as the real root, the above factorization works for any root.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The trick can be repeated.
 Although at first it might seem daunting, the pattern is uniform: every
 power of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 occurred in the above.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $s\ne r$
\end_inset

 be some other root.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
q_{b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}\cdots b_{k-1}b_{k}}\left(z\right)=\left(z-r\right)\left(z-s\right)\left(z^{k-1}+\left(s+q_{b_{0}}\right)z^{k-2}+\left(s^{2}+sq_{b_{0}}+q_{b_{o}b_{1}}\right)z^{k-3}+\cdots\right)
\]

\end_inset

The coefficient of the next term being 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{3}+s^{2}q_{b_{0}}+sq_{b_{o}b_{1}}+q_{b_{0}b_{1}b_{2}}$
\end_inset

 and so on.
 From this point one, this becomes just an ordinary factorization of polynomials...
 well, but so was the first step, as well.
 What made the first step interesting was that, because the coefficients
 at that step were explicitly either zero or one, the corresponding reversal
 of the bit sequence became manifest.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
One may as well bring this detour to a close.
 There's nothing particularly magic in the above factorization, other than
 the combinatorial re-arrangement of the polynomial labels.
 A generic polynomial factorization looks like the below, for comparison.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p\left(x\right)=x^{n+1}+c_{0}x^{n}+c_{1}x^{n-1}+\cdots c_{n}
\]

\end_inset

and if 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a root of 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(x\right)$
\end_inset

 
\emph on
viz
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\left(r\right)=0$
\end_inset

 then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
p\left(x\right)= & \left(x-r\right)\left(x^{n}+\left(r+c_{0}\right)x^{n-1}+\left(r^{2}+c_{0}r+c_{1}\right)x^{n-2}+\cdots\right)\\
= & \left(x-r\right)\left(x^{n}+a_{0}x^{n-1}+a_{1}x^{n-2}+\cdots\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
a_{k}=r^{k+1}+\sum_{j=0}^{k}c_{j}r^{k-j}
\]

\end_inset

