\begin_layout Standard
The bracketing relationship can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k-1}\right]\Mapsto\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]\Mapsfrom\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{p}-1\right]
\]

\end_inset

with where 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is the largest integer 
\begin_inset Formula $1<p\le k-1$
\end_inset

 for which 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{p}\ne0$
\end_inset

.
 The notation here is that each label is brackets by a pair of shorter labels,
 on the left, and on the right.
 Each label corresponds to a specific 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 value; write 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]\right)$
\end_inset

 for this value.
 The bracketing relationship states that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k-1}\right]\right)<\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]\right)<\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{p}-1\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

with the inequalities being strict.
 Each interval is of decreasing size, limiting to zero, as the length of
 the integer sequences expand.
 As the bounds are increasingly tight, they bracket a unique convergent.
 
\end_layout

