\begin_layout Standard
The use of the word 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

odometer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 is perhaps a bit cryptic; a quick review is in order.
 An odometer of characteristic 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 is defined as the set of all infinite-length integer sequences 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{0},a_{1},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

 with each 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{k}$
\end_inset

 drawn from the cyclic group 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Z}/p\mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

.
 This set is endowed with a transition function 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 given by the map 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T\left(a_{0},a_{1},\cdots\right)\mapsto\begin{cases}
\left(a_{0}+1,a_{1},\cdots\right) & \mbox{if }a_{0}\ne p-1\\
\left(0,\cdots,0,a_{k}+1,a_{k+1},\cdots\right) & \mbox{if }\left(a_{0},a_{1},\cdots\right)=\left(p-1,\cdots,p-1,a_{k},a_{k+1},\cdots\right)
\end{cases}
\]

\end_inset

That is, it increments 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{0}$
\end_inset

 by one, and if that rolls over, then a carry bit is propagated to the next
 term, and so on.
 This is just 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic addition, treated as a dynamical system.
 It can also be interpreted as a map of the unit interval, to itself, when
 the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a_{0},a_{1},\cdots\right)$
\end_inset

 is interpreted as 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\sum_{n}a_{n}p^{-n-1}$
\end_inset

.
 As a map of the unit interval, it permutes a countable sequence of intervals
 of decreasing size.
 Odometers are bijections of the unit interval into itself.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

-odometer can be taken to be an odometer of characteristic zero.
 The rationale for this opaque claim can be clarified by looking at how
 it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

rolls over
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 The prototypical roll-over occurs at the juncture of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\varphi=1.618\cdots$
\end_inset

.
 One observes the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left[0,1\right] & =\beta=1.75488\cdots\\
\left[0,2\right] & =\beta=1.70490\cdots\\
 & \vdots\\
\left[0,16\right] & =\beta=1.61816\cdots\\
\left[0,N\right] & =\beta>\varphi\mbox{ for }N\to\infty\\
\left[0\right]=\left[1,-1\right]=\left[1,0,0,\cdots\right] & =\beta=\varphi\\
\left[1,0,0,\cdots,1,\cdots\right] & =\beta<\varphi
\end{align*}

\end_inset

That is, the sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,N\right]$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

 rolls over to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[1,0,0,\cdots\right]$
\end_inset

.
 It is this peculiar behavior that merits the name 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

odometer
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Analogously, a rollover happens at every finite string.
 The bracketing relation supplies a descending sequence leading up to the
 rollover:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,N\right]\right)<\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,N-1\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

At the rollover point, the final digit is dropped:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]\right)<\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k},N\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

After the rollover, 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}+1,0\right]\right)<\beta\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots,m_{k}\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Unlike the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic case, there is no way to increment/decrement the odometer by one unit
 so as to maintain the total order on 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

.
 Incrementing the first digit gives a sequence 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta\left(\left[N\right]\right)$
\end_inset

 that approaches 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=1$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $N\to\infty$
\end_inset

, but it has nowhere to rollover to.
 There's no way to get to the last digit of an infinite string, to increment
 that.
 The best one can do is to write out the expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

, decrement by some arbitrarily small 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and notice that the expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta-\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 has rolled over at some location.
 The increment is, formally speaking, an infinitesimal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

-adic odometers are interval maps; they re-arrange countable sequences of
 subintervals of the unit interval.
 Here, likewise, the beta odometer rearranges intervals, at least in the
 sense that rearrangements are disjoint.
 So, the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\varphi,2\right)$
\end_inset

 is mapped to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{2},1\right)$
\end_inset

 albeit in a fractal manner, and likewise each subinterval bounded by the
 descending series of roots to 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{n}-\beta^{n-1}-1=0$
\end_inset

 is mapped to the interval 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\frac{1}{n},\frac{1}{n-1}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 By self-symmetry, the sub-intervals will re-arrange as well.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A precise expression for the self-symmetry is easy to write in symbolic
 form.
 There are two, actually; one is a shift:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g:\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\mapsto\left[m_{1}+1,m_{2},\cdots\right]
\]

\end_inset

and the other is a reflection.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
r:\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\mapsto\left[1,m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]
\]

\end_inset

When the sequences are interpreted as continued fractions, they have a ready
 expression:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\left(r\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\right)\right)=c\left(\left[1,m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\right)=1-c\left(\left[m_{1},m_{2},\cdots\right]\right)
\]

\end_inset

that is, 
\begin_inset Formula $r\left(x\right)=1-x$
\end_inset

; thus a reflection.
 The shift acting on the continued fractions is likewise a Möbius transformation
: 
\begin_inset Formula $g\left(x\right)=x/\left(x+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 By contrast, there is no obvious simple expression for 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 in terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 for the odometer.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Together, these two generate the dyadic monoid.
 That is, a general expression 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a}\circ r\circ g^{b}\circ\cdots$
\end_inset

 is still a self-symmetry of the odometer.
 Such elements can be put in one-to-one correspondence with the infinite
 binary tree, i.e.
 the dyadic monoid.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Islands of Stability as Arnold Tongues
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Islands-of-Stability"

\end_inset


