\begin_layout Standard
The trouble-spots, the eventual fixed-points of the map, can be placed in
 one-to-one accordance with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

islands of stability
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 seen in the iterated logistic map.
 They are, in essence, locations where periodic orbits 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

could be pasted
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, or where they 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

naturally would appear
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, if the map supported periodic attractors.
 That is, the beta shift only supports a single attractor, of period-one
 at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

; there is no 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

room
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 for anything more.
 This is analogous, in a way, to the phase locked loop, at zero coupling
 constant.
 At finite coupling strength, these 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

trouble spots
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 expand out as Arnold tongues, to have a finite size, visible on the Feigenbaum
 diagram for the logistic map as regions where period-doubling is occurring.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea here can be illustrated explicitly.
 Basically, take the natural saw-tooth shape of the map, widen the middle,
 and insert a slanting downward line, to create a zig-zag.
 That is, connect the two endpoints in the middle of the beta shift, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

widening
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 it so that it has a finite, not infinite slope, thereby converting the
 iterated function from a discontinuous to a continuous one.
 This can be constructed directly: given some 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

small
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, real 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon>0$
\end_inset

, define the piecewise-linear 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

-generalization of the map 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:downshift"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
T_{\beta,\varepsilon}(x)=\begin{cases}
\beta x & \mbox{ for }0\le x<\frac{1}{2}-\varepsilon\\
\frac{\beta}{4}-\beta\left(\frac{1}{4}-\varepsilon\right)w & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}-\varepsilon\le x<\frac{1}{2}+\varepsilon\\
\beta\left(x-\frac{1}{2}\right) & \mbox{ for }\frac{1}{2}+\varepsilon\le x\le1
\end{cases}\label{eq:zig-zag map}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is just a handy notation for a downward sloping line:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w=\frac{2x-1}{2\varepsilon}
\]

\end_inset

Observe that 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{2}-\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 and that 
\begin_inset Formula $w=-1$
\end_inset

 when 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\frac{1}{2}+\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 just smoothly interpolates between +1 and -1 over the middle interval.
 The additional factors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\beta}{4}-\beta\left(\frac{1}{4}-\varepsilon\right)w$
\end_inset

 just serves to insert the downward slope smack into the middle, so that
 the endpoints join up.
 The results is the zig-zag map, illustrated in the figure below
